// ╔══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
// ║                    NATCOM TUTORIAL GUIDE                         ║
// ║        Learn the world's first English programming language      ║
// ╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

// Welcome to NATCOM! Our objective is to make coding perfect, professional, 
// and entirely barrier-free. You write in plain English. The compiler does the rest.

// ── 1. VARIABLES ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
// You can create integers, floats, strings, and booleans.
Create a high speed integer named Age and set it to 25.
Create a floating point variable named Pi and set it to 3.14.
Create a string named Developer and set it to "Beon".
Create a boolean named IsAwesome and set it to true.

// ── 2. OUTPUT ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// Use 'Display' for text, and 'Log' or 'Display the values of' for variables.
Display "Welcome to the NATCOM Tutorial!"
Display the values of Developer.
Log the value of IsAwesome.

// ── 3. USER INPUT ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
// Ask the user for numbers or text.
Ask the user to enter a value for Age.
Ask the user for text named Developer.

// ── 4. MATH & OPERATIONS ──────────────────────────────────────────
// Math is just verbs.
Add 5 to Age.
Subtract 2 from Age.
Multiply Pi by 2.0.

Create a high speed integer named Counter and set it to 0.
Increment Counter.
Decrement Counter.

// ── 5. ADVANCED MATH ──────────────────────────────────────────────
Create a floating point variable named MathResult and set it to 0.
Set MathResult to the square root of Pi.

// ── 6. LOOPS ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// Repeat blocks of code.
Display "Counting to 3..."
Repeat 3 times:
  Increment Counter.
  Log the value of Counter.
Done.

// ── 7. CONDITIONALS (IF / OTHERWISE) ──────────────────────────────
If the Age is greater than 18, then:
  Display "You are an adult."
Otherwise:
  Display "You are a minor."

// ── 8. SYSTEM OVERRIDE (Advanced) ─────────────────────────────────
// Drop raw C code directly if you need absolute control.
<SYSTEM_OVERRIDE>
printf("This is raw C code injected into the matrix.\n");
</SYSTEM_OVERRIDE>

Display "Tutorial Complete. You are now a NATCOM Master."
